{"data":{"currentPage":{"html":"<h1>Introduction</h1>\n<p><em>chart-parts</em> is a flexible <a href=\"https://www.springer.com/us/book/9780387245447\">Grammar-of-Graphics</a> rendering pipeline designed for application developers.</p>\n<h2>Project Vision</h2>\n<p>In his seminal book <em>The Grammar of Graphics</em>, Leland Wilkinson envisioned a system of charting components and data-flows to support charts. There have been several systems that have implemented these ideas, most recently Vega, Vega-Lite and Altair.</p>\n<p><img src=\"/images/wilkinson_book.png\" alt=\"Wilkinson&#x27;s Book\"></p>\n<p>The vision of <code class=\"language-text\">chart-parts</code> is to support the <em>rendering phases</em> of Wilkinson's pipeline in a flexible, architecture-agnostic way while dovetailing nicely with React. To date, implementations of the <em>Grammar of Graphics</em> have tended to exist as closed systems. While a closed system can be useful for certain users, and for certain abstraction levels, we believe that a closed graphical system should be built on top of an open graphics system to allow for maximum architectural flexibility.</p>","htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"h1","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Introduction"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"chart-parts"}]},{"type":"text","value":" is a flexible "},{"type":"element","tagName":"a","properties":{"href":"https://www.springer.com/us/book/9780387245447"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Grammar-of-Graphics"}]},{"type":"text","value":" rendering pipeline designed for application developers."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h2","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Project Vision"}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In his seminal book "},{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The Grammar of Graphics"}]},{"type":"text","value":", Leland Wilkinson envisioned a system of charting components and data-flows to support charts. There have been several systems that have implemented these ideas, most recently Vega, Vega-Lite and Altair."}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"img","properties":{"src":"/images/wilkinson_book.png","alt":"Wilkinson's Book"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The vision of "},{"type":"element","tagName":"code","properties":{"className":["language-text"]},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"chart-parts"}]},{"type":"text","value":" is to support the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"rendering phases"}]},{"type":"text","value":" of Wilkinson's pipeline in a flexible, architecture-agnostic way while dovetailing nicely with React. To date, implementations of the "},{"type":"element","tagName":"em","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Grammar of Graphics"}]},{"type":"text","value":" have tended to exist as closed systems. While a closed system can be useful for certain users, and for certain abstraction levels, we believe that a closed graphical system should be built on top of an open graphics system to allow for maximum architectural flexibility."}]}],"data":{"quirksMode":false}},"frontmatter":{"date":null,"path":"/documentation/introduction","title":"Introduction"}},"toc":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Architecture","path":"/documentation/introduction/architecture","order":2}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Concepts","path":"/documentation/concepts","order":1}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"title":"History & Related Work","path":"/documentati